00:49:13,669 --> 00:49:15,830
Appreciate it.

1049
00:49:15,890 --> 00:49:17,750
Sorry, you've got lines on the other side.

1050
00:49:17,770 --> 00:49:19,011
Oh, my bad.

1051
00:49:19,131 --> 00:49:19,851
Oh my goodness.

1052
00:49:19,871 --> 00:49:20,211
Sorry.

1053
00:49:21,191 --> 00:49:21,531
Go ahead.

1054
00:49:21,712 --> 00:49:22,172
I'm here too.

1055
00:49:22,252 --> 00:49:22,632
Okay, hi.

1056
00:49:23,192 --> 00:49:26,113
I was wondering, variants that spawn other cards,

1057
00:49:26,193 --> 00:49:27,173
like don't show that variant.

1058
00:49:27,193 --> 00:49:28,654
Like if I play a baby Dr. Doom,

1059
00:49:28,794 --> 00:49:30,014
I don't get baby Doom bots.

1060
00:49:30,174 --> 00:49:30,514
Why?

1061
00:49:33,621 --> 00:49:34,561
It's a great question.

1062
00:49:34,581 --> 00:49:36,682
Sorry, you don't get like,

1063
00:49:37,642 --> 00:49:38,723
the cards that spawn other cards,

1064
00:49:38,783 --> 00:49:41,263
the cards that they spawn are not variants of the...

1065
00:49:41,283 --> 00:49:45,345
Yeah, I mean it was something that we would like to do

1066
00:49:45,705 --> 00:49:46,905
at some point, I think it would be great.

1067
00:49:47,105 --> 00:49:48,906
We also want to do variants for cards

1068
00:49:48,926 --> 00:49:50,806
that are spawned by locations, like rock variants.

1069
00:49:51,266 --> 00:49:52,507
By the way, Dwayne The Rock Johnson,

1070
00:49:52,527 --> 00:49:53,847
if you're watching this, please hit us up.

1071
00:49:53,867 --> 00:49:55,808
We'd love to do a rock variant together.

1072
00:49:57,308 --> 00:49:57,668
Thank you.

1073
00:49:58,008 --> 00:49:58,669
We'd love to do it, thanks.

1074
00:49:59,289 --> 00:49:59,649
Okay, over there.

1075
00:50:00,401 --> 00:50:05,425
So you discussed complexity versus depth and how a card that says just deal two damage

1076
00:50:05,845 --> 00:50:08,707
still can have a lot of depth and hit the depth limit that you need.

1077
00:50:09,328 --> 00:50:13,331
But eventually you've printed deal two damage and you have to start like, you know,

1078
00:50:13,391 --> 00:50:15,192
complexity creep and so forth and so on.

1079
00:50:15,473 --> 00:50:19,636
And I was wondering what your strategies are for, you know, six, ten years into the game

1080
00:50:19,656 --> 00:50:23,879
and when all the simple cards are printed, there are no more simple cards left, what to do?

1081
00:50:24,159 --> 00:50:26,601
Yeah, so the question is, yeah, you mine out the simple rules,

1082
00:50:26,621 --> 00:50:29,583
and then eventually you end up with only non-simple stuff.

1083
00:50:29,603 --> 00:50:29,923
What do you do?

1084
00:50:30,163 --> 00:50:31,444
I had a whole section of this talk called

1085
00:50:31,884 --> 00:50:37,128
The Primal Fear of Working on a Game with a Small Amount of Design Space.

1086
00:50:37,528 --> 00:50:38,309
It's horrifying.

1087
00:50:38,609 --> 00:50:40,730
So, both on Hearthstone and on Marvel Snap,

1088
00:50:40,850 --> 00:50:42,291
we—I got a point where we're like,

1089
00:50:42,952 --> 00:50:45,853
You know, we were looking at games like Magic the Gathering around 30 years later,

1090
00:50:45,893 --> 00:50:47,634
and those games are much more complicated.

1091
00:50:47,954 --> 00:50:50,235
And so at least I imagine, I haven't been on those teams,

1092
00:50:50,255 --> 00:50:53,836
I imagine that they just don't have that same level of fear of like,

1093
00:50:53,896 --> 00:50:55,377
what if we just run out of all the cards?

1094
00:50:55,677 --> 00:50:58,178
At some point we will have designed all of the cards, right?

1095
00:50:58,198 --> 00:50:59,498
And that's it. We pack up shop.

1096
00:50:59,859 --> 00:51:02,900
But what happened actually on Hearthstone was that

1097
00:51:03,240 --> 00:51:06,782
there was a huge amount of design space, much, much, much more than I thought.

1098
00:51:07,082 --> 00:51:08,223
There was at the start.

1099
00:51:08,623 --> 00:51:13,787
And so, you know, it's scary to trim back and end up with a very limited amount of design space,

1100
00:51:14,227 --> 00:51:18,830
but it's just never borne out in the scary way where there's nothing left to do.

1101
00:51:19,251 --> 00:51:21,092
We always find more design space.

1102
00:51:21,412 --> 00:51:23,274
It can get more and more challenging over time,

1103
00:51:23,674 --> 00:51:26,876
but it's never run into the spot where we haven't ended up there.

1104
00:51:27,117 --> 00:51:28,257
Now, over time...

1105
00:51:28,918 --> 00:51:32,099
Your audience will stop growing, potentially, right?

1106
00:51:32,119 --> 00:51:35,120
Like, you know, we all wish audiences keep growing,

1107
00:51:35,140 --> 00:51:37,200
but at some point, maybe it's not as true.

1108
00:51:37,740 --> 00:51:40,521
And at that point, the complexity wall at the start

1109
00:51:41,161 --> 00:51:42,462
is not the thing that matters as much.

1110
00:51:43,442 --> 00:51:45,203
It's the additional complexity you're adding.

1111
00:51:45,423 --> 00:51:48,183
And so all the current players have already paid all the complexity costs.

1112
00:51:48,524 --> 00:51:50,645
And so if you add a new mechanic or a new card type

1113
00:51:50,685 --> 00:51:52,606
or a new zone or something, you just

1114
00:51:52,646 --> 00:51:55,047
have to teach them that little bit of additional complexity.

1115
00:51:55,447 --> 00:51:57,528
So you can add design space over time

1116
00:51:57,588 --> 00:52:00,110
to give yourself more room to design more stuff.

1117
00:52:00,610 --> 00:52:01,110
Thank you so much.

1118
00:52:02,311 --> 00:52:02,451
Yes.

1119
00:52:04,312 --> 00:52:05,433
Thanks.

1120
00:52:05,493 --> 00:52:07,114
Most mobile games, including Hearthstone,

1121
00:52:07,134 --> 00:52:08,354
they're horizontal, right?

1122
00:52:08,834 --> 00:52:11,956
At what point did you decide to use a vertical orientation?

1123
00:52:12,857 --> 00:52:14,037
What design space did that open?

1124
00:52:14,157 --> 00:52:15,958
Or did you just do it so I could play

1125
00:52:15,978 --> 00:52:17,219
while I'm driving or holding?

1126
00:52:17,559 --> 00:52:17,959
Yeah, right.

1127
00:52:19,360 --> 00:52:20,781
Please don't play Marvel's Devil While You're Driving.

1128
00:52:23,562 --> 00:52:26,183
So the question is, when did it, and why did we

1129
00:52:26,203 --> 00:52:27,864
decide to do vertical orientation?

1130
00:52:28,924 --> 00:52:32,866
I think we really wanted to make a mobile-first collectible card

1131
00:52:32,906 --> 00:52:33,106
game.

1132
00:52:33,546 --> 00:52:35,967
Most other collectible card games that are on mobile

1133
00:52:36,307 --> 00:52:40,629
feel like, or are ports of PC card games.

1134
00:52:40,689 --> 00:52:42,630
And we thought, this is just.

1135
00:52:43,290 --> 00:52:46,031
If we want this to be the best mobile collectible card game ever made,

1136
00:52:46,331 --> 00:52:47,992
I think we wanted to start vertical.

1137
00:52:48,032 --> 00:52:52,053
So we just always started the whole game with that kind of as a design constraint,

1138
00:52:52,713 --> 00:52:54,794
and tried to make sure that every decision we made...

1139
00:52:54,994 --> 00:52:56,635
We tried some weird stuff, like...

1140
00:52:57,775 --> 00:52:59,836
We weren't sure if we could fit all the locations on the screen, so...

1141
00:53:00,056 --> 00:53:03,517
We had like a carousel of locations you could swipe back and forth between,

1142
00:53:03,537 --> 00:53:04,057
and that did not...

1143
00:53:04,497 --> 00:53:05,698
We didn't end up going that direction, but...

1144
00:53:05,998 --> 00:53:07,738
We were that committed to a vertical display.

1145
00:53:09,089 --> 00:53:10,989
Thank you, appreciate it.

1146
00:53:11,009 --> 00:53:13,730
So I have a question about the simplicity

1147
00:53:13,850 --> 00:53:15,210
of your text on the card.

1148
00:53:15,530 --> 00:53:19,551
So how to fix the issue of being some misunderstanding

1149
00:53:19,591 --> 00:53:20,511
when the text is short?

1150
00:53:20,911 --> 00:53:23,032
Because sometimes I don't really understand

1151
00:53:23,052 --> 00:53:26,852
the whole mechanics, so I need to try

1152
00:53:26,872 --> 00:53:28,873
so I can know the real mechanics.

1153
00:53:28,893 --> 00:53:31,293
Because the other cards, I put in there

1154
00:53:31,553 --> 00:53:33,454
extreme circumstance on the card,

1155
00:53:33,654 --> 00:53:34,754
but you're not using this.

1156
00:53:34,774 --> 00:53:36,394
So how do you address this issue

1157
00:53:36,434 --> 00:53:38,795
of possible misunderstanding?

1158
00:53:38,955 --> 00:53:43,759
Yeah, so the question is about what you do when there's a clash between wanting short

1159
00:53:43,840 --> 00:53:47,243
card text but being clear and making sure that people actually understand what you're

1160
00:53:47,263 --> 00:53:47,463
saying.

1161
00:53:48,044 --> 00:53:48,624
You know, it's interesting.

1162
00:53:48,644 --> 00:53:52,889
There's a bunch of cards, I think it was called Shadow Madness in Hearthstone, which says

1163
00:53:52,949 --> 00:53:56,772
take control of an enemy minion like this turn only.

1164
00:53:57,273 --> 00:53:59,635
And what it doesn't say is that it gives the minion charge, right?

1165
00:54:00,035 --> 00:54:02,617
If you took control of an enemy minion, you wouldn't normally be able to attack with it.

1166
00:54:03,017 --> 00:54:08,419
But the fact that it's only for this turn, it's obvious that you must be able to attack with it.

1167
00:54:08,479 --> 00:54:10,340
And so we just kind of left that off the card.

1168
00:54:11,041 --> 00:54:14,282
There's some stuff, there's some types of designs where you can just say,

1169
00:54:14,342 --> 00:54:15,423
look, this is like a little bit...

1170
00:54:16,524 --> 00:54:20,607
We don't explain everything, but you can just try it,

1171
00:54:21,348 --> 00:54:23,570
and you'll learn after the first time.

1172
00:54:23,610 --> 00:54:28,295
And ideally, the best scenario for you

1173
00:54:28,335 --> 00:54:29,296
is the thing that actually happens.

1174
00:54:29,596 --> 00:54:31,298
We often, when showing people cards,

1175
00:54:31,398 --> 00:54:32,439
and they ask a question like, well,

1176
00:54:32,459 --> 00:54:34,260
I'm not sure about this edge case,

1177
00:54:34,681 --> 00:54:35,662
we say, well, what do you think?

1178
00:54:36,983 --> 00:54:37,803
What's your suspicion?

1179
00:54:38,223 --> 00:54:39,384
And we would write it down.

1180
00:54:39,504 --> 00:54:41,425
And if the suspicion is the correct thing,

1181
00:54:41,965 --> 00:54:43,666
it might be worth it for us to have less text.

1182
00:54:43,726 --> 00:54:44,367
Because they would be like,

1183
00:54:44,387 --> 00:54:45,587
I'm not sure, but I think it's going to do this.

1184
00:54:46,088 --> 00:54:47,608
That was good enough for us in a lot of cases.

1185
00:54:48,689 --> 00:54:51,911
But yeah, if the answer was they got the wrong thing

1186
00:54:51,991 --> 00:54:52,751
or they couldn't guess,

1187
00:54:53,191 --> 00:54:54,212
we would try and rewrite the card,

1188
00:54:54,252 --> 00:54:55,693
even if it meant adding more text.

1189
00:54:56,333 --> 00:54:59,075
So follow the intuitive software.

1190
00:54:59,455 --> 00:55:00,075
What was that?

1191
00:55:00,115 --> 00:55:02,016
Follow the intuitive software.

1192
00:55:02,456 --> 00:55:03,297
Yes, right.

1193
00:55:03,357 --> 00:55:04,718
We try to make it intuitive, exactly.

1194
00:55:04,998 --> 00:55:05,378
Thank you, sir.

1195
00:55:05,618 --> 00:55:06,138
Thank you, appreciate it.

1196
00:55:08,117 --> 00:55:09,798
Thank you, I have so many questions.

1197
00:55:09,938 --> 00:55:12,680
But I do want to ask about Fatui.

1198
00:55:13,400 --> 00:55:15,681
You talked about how a lot of design

1199
00:55:15,741 --> 00:55:18,983
is going into how to minimize the zero-sum game

1200
00:55:19,023 --> 00:55:21,324
and also using things like bot

1201
00:55:21,384 --> 00:55:23,084
to increase player satisfaction.

1202
00:55:23,104 --> 00:55:26,026
So I'm wondering what are some design iteration

1203
00:55:26,046 --> 00:55:29,648
or choices that went into the first-time player experience

1204
00:55:29,688 --> 00:55:33,489
to make sure that players have that sort of satisfaction

1205
00:55:33,770 --> 00:55:35,150
and how that impact, you know, like,

1206
00:55:35,590 --> 00:55:40,933
What kind of cards they get when they first play the game, and if they're going to see any bots, etc.

1207
00:55:40,953 --> 00:55:47,757
Yeah, so I basically, for both the Hearthstone first-time user experience,

1208
00:55:47,797 --> 00:55:53,660
I'm sorry, the question was how do we make sure that Fatui is awesome, especially with the zero-sum component.

1209
00:55:54,100 --> 00:55:58,282
Yeah, or just any design-related consideration with the Fatui.

1210
00:55:58,902 --> 00:56:05,965
So the entire Fatui for Hearthstone and Marvel Snap is just copied from George Fan's talk that I mentioned.

1211
00:56:05,985 --> 00:56:10,147
We just laid it out and we just copied it. It's like exactly that.

